did.unittitle: Indiana University Department of English records
did.abstract: The English Department records span more than a century, from 1886 to 2012. The collection consists of correspondence between the acting chairman and English faculty members at IU and other institutions in the United States as well as students. The administrative files contain memos, correspondence with IU English faculty and regional campuses, reports pertaining to department committees, programs, courses, publications, other activities that concerned the development and growth of the Department. The publications files contain journals and other published material relating to Bloomington's English department.

accessrestrict.head: Access Restrictions
accessrestrict.p: Select files are closed to researchers. These are indicated in the finding aid.

bioghist.head: Administrative History
bioghist.p: While English classes at IU date back to 1829, it was not until the 1840s that the department began to specialize in classical languages and literatures. In 1861, department chair Henry Bascom Hibbens left to join the Union Army, and the department lacked a central figure until 1868 when George Washington Hoss became the new chairman. Hoss made some significant changes, most notably adding English to the catalogue as an elective (it would not be until 1880 that Chairman Orrin Benner Clark listed courses in the catalogue under the heading "Department of English.") In addition to expanding the curriculum, Clark introduced a written exercise for all IU students and placed an emphasis on literature. Seven years later, in 1887, the department awarded its first M.A. degree.

In the late 1890s and early 1900s, Clark's successor Martin Wright Sampson expanded the emphasis on literature to include literary history and critical study. Sampson also turned his attention to high schools and raised awareness that incoming freshman needed established writing and literary skills to succeed at IU.

By 1899, the English Department contained eight of the university's seventy-one faculty members. In 1908, the department offered its first graduate courses, and six years later it granted its first Ph.D. to Lillian B. Brownsfield (ten years later, Sister Gertrude Smith would receive the second Ph.D. awarded by the department). In 1920, following the resignation of numerous faculty and staff members, the English Department took on a new face as a younger generation of teachers entered the department and by 1921 it had expanded to 24 faculty members. For the next twenty-five years, while the department continued to grow, it experienced a period of relative stability while focusing on the teaching of composition and literary history.

Though the English Department experienced a slight reduction of students during World War II, the department reasserted itself after the war, under the chairmanship of James A. Work (1951-1961), by establishing a variety of outreach programs, such as the Writing Laboratory and a Poetry Series sponsored by Indiana University Press. By revising the undergraduate and honors programs in 1953, Work helped gain national recognition for the department. The graduate program was revised in 1961. In the 1960s the department implemented other programs, such as an English language program for undergraduates in 1966 and a guest speaker seminar series in 1968. In the 1970s, the English Department added a Comparative Literature Program.
Currently, the English Department has approximately 60 faculty members, 200 graduate students, and 500 undergraduate majors.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Collection is organized into three series: Correspondence, Administrative files, and Publications.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Note
scopecontent.p: The English Department records span the period from 1886 and 2012 with the bulk of the material created in the period from 1940 to 1980. The records are organized into three series: Correspondence, Administrative files, and Publications.

The Correspondence series contains two sub-series: General correspondence, and Student correspondence. Since most of the correspondence was written to and from English department chairs, the folders have been organized by the person writing to the chairman or to whom the chairman addressed his letter. The General correspondence sub-series, 1922-1971, consists of correspondence from faculty at IU, faculty members from institutions throughout the United States and other countries, prospective and current students, alumni, and individuals associated with various businesses. The Student correspondence sub-series, 1924-1964, is comprised of letters to and from prospective and current students as well as alumni. In the original accession, these files were kept separate from the general correspondence, so the original order has been maintained. Correspondents who wrote or received more than two letters have been placed in their own folder, while the remaining correspondents have been placed in "General" folders located at the end of the appropriate alphabetical section. All the folders in the sub-series are arranged alphabetically by the last name of the correspondent and then chronologically within the folder. Nicknames have been placed in parenthesis after the correspondent's name.

While most individual folders contain only a few pieces of correspondence, the acting chairman frequently corresponded with several IU faculty and administrators, such as the Dean of Men, C.E. Edmonson, the Dean of the School of Music, Wilfred C. Bain, Professor Edgar L. Yeager of the Psychology Department, Professor Norman Pratt, Jr. of the Classics Department, and Professor Bert E. Young of the Romance Language Department. The acting chairman also recurrently corresponded with faculty and administrative members at other institutions, such as Professor R.W. Pence of DePauw University and Alfred H. Upham, President of the University of Idaho and Miami University (Oxford, OH).

The Administrative files series contains four sub-series: Committees; General subject; Programs; and Regional campuses. These sub-series have been arranged alphabetically by subject and then chronologically within the folder. The Committees sub-series, 1953-1999, primarily contains memos and interdepartmental correspondence that discuss appointments for faculty and staff, as well as curriculum issues. Several of the folders contain committee meeting minutes and agendas that address curriculum matters, such as potential new courses as well as changes to current courses. The sub-series also includes some correspondence between the English department and various IU administrative offices. The General subject sub-series, 1943-2012, contain records on a wide variety of issues that pertain to the growth and development of the English Department, mainly in the 1950s and 1960s. The sub-series contains interdepartmental correspondence along with memoranda with select IU administrative offices regarding curriculum matters and course offerings. Some folders contain reports pertaining to curriculum matters, such as course proposals and alterations, while other folders relate to more administrative affairs, such as problems with graduate examinations and teaching load requirements. Also found here are files on the history of the department, gathered as part of project in the late 1960s. Included in the files are memoirs and reminiscences of faculty and alumni from acros the years. The series also includes some funding requests for various projects the department sought to develop. The Programs sub-series, 1956-1976, mainly consists of interdepartmental correspondence on the various programs that the English department pursued and developed. Most of the folders contain memos that discuss proposals and funding requests for the programs. Unlike the other folders in this series, the comparative literature program file consists mostly of course and curriculum information documenting the debates among faculty and administrative officials on how best to develop the program. The sub-series, Regional campuses, 1964-1972, is comprised of correspondence between the English department at IU and the English departments at other IU campuses. Since Bloomington's English department served as a guide for the development and growth of other the other departments, the correspondence primarily pertains to faculty issues, such as faculty openings and potential candidates to fill the new positions. Also, various memoranda discuss the types of courses the branch campuses offered and the recommendations for making changes in curriculums.

The final series, the Publications series, 1943-2012, consists primarily of departmental newsletters and its working papers but also includes other departmental publications such as The Ballantinian, The Folio, Pegasus, Quarry, and departmental manuals.

separatedmaterial.head: Separated Material
separatedmaterial.p: Records containing social security numbers have been removed and placed in restricted folders. Duplicate records have been removed.
Two photographs have been pulled and transferred to the University Archives Photograph Collection.

userestrict.head: Usage Restrictions
userestrict.p: Copyrights for records originating with Indiana University administrative units, departments, and other offices are held by the Trustees of Indiana University. For more information, please contact the Indiana University Archives staff.

The Indiana University Archives respects the intellectual property rights of others and does not claim any copyrights for non-university records, materials in the public domain, or materials for which we do not hold a Deed of Gift. Responsibility for the determination of the copyright status of these materials rests with those persons wishing to reuse the materials. Researchers are responsible for securing permission from copyright owners and any other rights holders for any reuse of these materials that extends beyond fair use or other statutory limitations.

Digital reproductions of archival materials from the Indiana University Archives are made available for noncommercial educational and research purposes only. If you are the copyright holder for any of the digitized materials and have questions about its inclusion on our site, please contact the Indiana University Archivist.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p: [Item], Indiana University Department of English records, Collection C287, Indiana University Archives, Bloomington.

custodhist.head: Provenance
custodhist.p: Transferred from the English Department to the University Archives, 29 July 1987.
Additional records transferred in 2008 by former department chair Donald J. Gray.
Issues of Pegasus (volumes 1-5, 1962-1967) were transferred from the Herman B Wells Library Research Collection to the University Archives in July 2019.

appraisal.head: Appraisal
appraisal.p: Duplicate records have been removed. Several newspaper clippings have been photocopied and the original articles discarded.
